Your custom exception class, named `CommandExecutionException`, should inherit from the standard `std::exception` class and provide a constructor that accepts a `const std::string&` message parameter. Additionally, you need to implement the `what()` method to return the error message associated with the exception.

Your task is to complete the implementation of the `CommandExecutionException` class and demonstrate its usage in a sample program.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

// Define the custom exception class CommandExecutionException here

class Command {
public:
    void execute() {
        throw CommandExecutionException("Error executing command: Invalid input");
    }
};

int main() {
    try {
        Command cmd;
        cmd.execute();
    } catch (const CommandExecutionException& ex) {
        std::cerr << "Command execution error: " << ex.what() << std::endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

