Below is the complete and executable code snippet that implements a simple server-client communication system using C++ and the SFML library. The server will listen on port 55001 for incoming connections and send a welcome message to any connected client, which will then display the message.

```cpp
#include <SFML/Network.hpp>
#include <iostream>
#include <thread>

void startServer()
{
    // Server setup to listen on port 55001
    sf::TcpListener listener;
    if (listener.listen(55001) != sf::Socket::Done)
    {
        std::cerr << "Error starting the server!" << std::endl;
        return;
    }

    std::cout << "Server is running on port 55001..." << std::endl;

    // Endless loop that waits for new connections
    while (true)
    {
        sf::TcpSocket client;
        if (listener.accept(client) == sf::Socket::Done)
        {
            // A new client just connected!
            std::string message = "Welcome to the server!";
            client.send(message.c_str(), message.length() + 1);
            std::cout << "Sent message to client: " << message << std::endl;
        }
    }
}

void startClient()
{
    sf::TcpSocket socket;
    if (socket.connect("127.0.0.1", 55001) == sf::Socket::Done)
    {
        char buffer[100];
        std::size_t received;
        if (socket.receive(buffer, sizeof(buffer), received) == sf::Socket::Done)
        {
            std::cout << "Received: " << buffer << std::endl;
        }
        else
        {
            std::cerr << "Error receiving message from server!" << std::endl;
        }
    }
    else
    {
        std::cerr << "Error connecting to the server!" << std::endl;
    }
}

int main()
{
    std::thread serverThread(startServer); // Start the server in a separate thread
    std::this_thread::sleep_for(std::chrono::seconds(1)); // Wait a moment for the server to start
    startClient(); // Start the client

    serverThread.join(); // Wait for the server thread to finish (it won't in this case)
    return 0;
}
```

### Explanation:
1. **Server Functionality**: The `startServer` function sets up a TCP listener on port 55001. It enters an infinite loop that waits for incoming connections. When a client successfully connects, it sends a welcome message.

2. **Client Functionality**: The `startClient` function attempts to connect to the server at `127.0.0.1` on port 55001. If the connection is successful, it waits to receive a message from the server and then outputs that message to the console.

3. **Threading**: The server runs in a separate thread to allow the client to connect immediately after the server starts. This ensures that both server and client can run simultaneously in the same program.

4. **Error Handling**: Simple error messages are printed to the console to inform the user if there are any issues starting the server, connecting the client, or receiving messages.

Make sure to have the SFML library properly set up in your development environment to compile and run this code.

